  "slug": "pastiera-napoletana",
  "title": "Pastiera napoletana",
  "subtitle": "Neapolitan Easter wheat-and-ricotta tart",
  "excerpt": "The Neapolitan Easter tart: a pasta frolla case filled with a mixture of cooked wheat berries, sheep's milk ricotta, eggs, orange blossom water, and candied peel. Dense, fragrant, and better after two days of resting. Made in the days before Easter and improved by the wait.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Pastiera napoletana is one of the oldest documented Italian baked goods, with references to a wheat-and-ricotta preparation in Neapolitan festive tradition traced to the sixteenth century. The modern form with orange blossom water and a pasta frolla case is described in Ippolito Cavalcanti, Cucina teorico-pratica (1837), and appears consistently in Neapolitan cookbooks through the twentieth century. Grano cotto (pre-cooked wheat) is the authentic base; canned grano cotto (Chirico brand or similar) is sold in Italian grocery shops.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pastiera is not a same-day bake. The filling and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "pasta frolla",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "pasta frolla",
                  "termId": "cmpazy0w30000bwv412dz1q1e"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " case need 48 hours to reach the correct texture: the filling firms, the fragrance of the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "orange blossom water",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "orange blossom water",
                  "termId": "cmpbaqbi10001n4v4bzh5nal9"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " rounds out, and the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "grano cotto",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "grano cotto",
                  "termId": "cmpbaqbha0000n4v4eyicbgr3"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " softens into the custard. Use canned grano cotto (Chirico or similar) to avoid a 3-hour wheat berry cook.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "title": "Plan ahead"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "text": "Make this on Thursday or Friday for Easter Sunday. The pastry dough can be made up to 3 days ahead and refrigerated. The assembled tart rests uncovered at cool room temperature for 48 hours after baking.",
                "type": "text"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
